data.title: It was Stevie Wonder’s first home in Detroit. The Supremes lived on St. Antoine. Even Young Boys Incorporated had territory in the Jects....
data.meta_description:
2,505 likes, 71 comments - blackdetroiters on August 18, 2023: "It was Stevie Wonder’s first home in Detroit. The Supremes lived on St. Antoine. Even Young Boys Incorporated had territory in the Jects. 

If you are going to Afro Nation Detroit this weekend, the Afrobeats festival will be held on the grounds of the former Brewster-Douglass Housing Projects. 

I guess they are calling it “Bedrock’s Douglass site” since Dan G owns it. Nasty work. 

But, the Brewsters were the first public housing project in America built specifically for Black people, in the 1930s. 

Townhomes were built first along Mack Ave. and then the towers or “14s” went up in the 1950s along I-75. The towers were officially called the Frederick Douglass Apartments and were 14 stories tall.

Those were demolished a decade ago, but a page called @thebrewstersprojects76 was curated to showcase Black life in the Projects in the 1970s. 

Give it a follow and remember the history and culture of the Brewster Projects and its Black residents.

#BlackDetroiters #BlackDetroit #Detroit #BrewsterProjects #AfroNation #AfroBeats".
